(128, 'ZDNet Log In | Join ZDNet Manage        Discussion Alerts Log Out header.nav.home         Hot Topics            Newsletters            White Papers            Reviews            Downloads      Edition ZDNet.com is available in the following editions: Asia Australia Europe India United Kingdom United States ZDNet around the globe: ZDNet Belgium ZDNet China ZDNet France ZDNet Germany ZDNet Korea ZDNet Japan Topics Security             Enterprise Software             Cloud             Apple             Tablets             Android             Microsoft             Open Source             Broadband             EU        Log In Log In Join ZDNet Manage Discussion Alerts Log Out   Topic: Innovation Follow via: RSSEmail Alert Samsung Galaxy S6 teardown Summary:Time to see what makes the new Samsung Galaxy S6 tick. Is this handset any easier to repair than the S6 Edge? By Adrian Kingsley-Hughes for Hardware 2.0 | April 14, 2015 -- 21:00 GMT (22:00 BST) Follow @the_pc_doc Get the newsletter now                                   0Comments                                                                                                                                       Email    Print    Google+    Del.icio.us    Digg    StumbleUpon    Reddit    Pinterest    Slashdot                           0Comments                                                     Email    Print    Google+    Del.icio.us    Digg    StumbleUpon    Reddit    Pinterest    Slashdot           Samsung''s long-awaited Galaxy S6 has fallen into the hands of the repair (and disassembly) experts over at iFixit who have done with it what they do best - taken it apart!   Must See Gallery The best HDMI operating system sticks There''s a new kind of computer in town and it''s resides on an HDMI stick that''s not much bigger than a pack of gum. Read More  One thing that''s pretty clear, just as with the S6 Edge, the S6 is not what you''d call an easily repairable handset. Again, this handset is sealed with lots of glue that necessitates the use of the iOpener to get past it all. And again the battery is hidden behind the midframe, making it difficult to replace.  Getting at the battery is doable - in fact it''s easier than for the S6 Edge - but you will need specialist tools, a lot of patience, and you will undoubtedly add a few dollars to the swear jar, especially if you happen to break the display or tear a cable.  Inside the S6 Edge the team came across a diverse array of parts, including a lot of Samsung-branded components:Samsung Exynos 7420 Octa-core 64-bit processor (2.1 GHz quad + 1.5 GHz quad)  Samsung K3RG3G30MM-DGCH 3 GB LPDDR4 RAM  Samsung KLUBG4G1BD 32GB NAND flash  Skyworks 78041 Hybrid Multimode Multiband (MMMB) Front-End Module (FEM)  Avago AFEM-9020 PAM  Broadcom BCM4773 GNSS Location Hub  Samsung C2N8AF (possibly image processor)  Avago A7007  Wolfson Microelectronics WM1840 Audio Codec  Samsung S2MPS15  Samsung Shannon 928 RF Transceiver  Maxim MAX77843 Companion PMIC  Maxim MAX98505 Class DG Audio Amplifier  Samsung Shannon 600B5D  STMicro FT6BH touchscreen controller   iFixit   iFixit   iFixit  All-in-all, the S6 is easier to repair than the S6 Edge, but only just. But that''s pretty much par of the course for all modern smartphones.   Previous  |  Next Image 1 of 5 Introduction There''s no doubt that the Samsung Galaxy S series\r of smartphones were the best Android handsets available, with the Galaxy S5\r being the king of the hill. But the more I look at Samsung''s new Galaxy S6, the\r more I think the company broke a winning design in order to compete with Apple''s iPhone.The Galaxy S6 might be a more modern\r handset, but it''s debatable as to whether it is a better design.Let''s take a look at what you''ll lose if\r you switch from the Galaxy S5 to the Galaxy S6.See also:Samsung''s Galaxy S6: How it was designedApple Watch: Things we need to knowApple Watch: Here are five business models it will disruptTech specs: Samsung Galaxy S6 and Galaxy S6 EdgeDeveloper gets Android Wear to work with the iPhoneSensor issues forced health features to be cut from Apple Watch Substituting plastic for glass Put an iPhone 6 and a Galaxy S5 side by\r side and they are like chalk and cheese. One is thin, sleek, glossy, beautiful,\r and fragile, while the other is chunky, plastic, rather utilitarian, and\r robust.Now do the same, but this time replacing\r the Galaxy S5 for the new Galaxy S6. Now both the handsets are thin, sleek,\r glossy, beautiful, and very fragile.I''ve seen Galaxy S5 handsets fall onto hard\r surfaces, skid for long distances across concrete, and even get slammed in car\r doors and driven over and survive pretty much unscathed. I seriously doubt that\r the Galaxy S6 will be able to do the same.Gorilla Glass is strong, but at the end of\r the day, glass is glass.See also:Samsung''s Galaxy S6: How it was designedApple Watch: Things we need to knowApple Watch: Here are five business models it will disruptTech specs: Samsung Galaxy S6 and Galaxy S6 EdgeDeveloper gets Android Wear to work with the iPhoneSensor issues forced health features to be cut from Apple Watch No more expandable storage If you''re used to augmenting the internal\r storage in your Galaxy S handset with a spare microSD card then I have bad news\r for you. There is no microSD card slot on the Galaxy S6.The Galaxy S5 could take a 128GB microSD\r card.Gone is the convenience of being able to\r load documents and movies and whatnot onto a storage card to take with you on\r the road. Now everything you want to do with your handset eats into your\r precious (and expensive) storage.See also:Samsung''s Galaxy S6: How it was designedApple Watch: Things we need to knowApple Watch: Here are five business models it will disruptTech specs: Samsung Galaxy S6 and Galaxy S6 EdgeDeveloper gets Android Wear to work with the iPhoneSensor issues forced health features to be cut from Apple Watch No more waterproofing While the Galaxy S5 wasn''t something you\r could take scuba diving, the gaskets and seals did offer a level of\r waterproofing that most handsets can''t offer.Here''s a video of the Galaxy S5 being put through its paces.Alas, in the name of making the Galaxy S6\r thin and light, those gaskets and seals are gone. So don''t try what you see in that video on your new Galaxy S6.See also:Samsung''s Galaxy S6: How it was designedApple Watch: Things we need to knowApple Watch: Here are five business models it will disruptTech specs: Samsung Galaxy S6 and Galaxy S6 EdgeDeveloper gets Android Wear to work with the iPhoneSensor issues forced health features to be cut from Apple Watch No more removable battery Finally, let us take a few moments to pay\r our respects to the removable battery feature. While few carry a spare battery\r around with them these days, having the option was nice, and when the handset\r was a few years old, you could quickly and easily (not to mention cheaply) swap\r out the battery to bring its charge capacity up to full.See also:Samsung''s Galaxy S6: How it was designedApple Watch: Things we need to knowApple Watch: Here are five business models it will disruptTech specs: Samsung Galaxy S6 and Galaxy S6 EdgeDeveloper gets Android Wear to work with the iPhoneSensor issues forced health features to be cut from Apple Watch Previous Next  See also:How to install multiple SIM cards into an iPhone 6  It''s taken months, but iOS 8.3 finally addresses Wi-Fi problems  KitKat and Lollipop running almost half of all Android devices  Samsung responds to S6/S6 Edge ''bending'' concerns  Essential PC, smartphone and tablet repair tools Topics: Innovation, Android, Hardware, Mobility, Smartphones About Adrian Kingsley-Hughes Adrian Kingsley-Hughes is an internationally published technology author who has devoted over a decade to helping users get the most from technology -- whether that be by learning to program, building a PC from a pile of parts, or helping them get the most from their new MP3 player or 