(165, 'FIND YOUR TV BY SIZE FIND YOUR TVBY SIZE 32" 40" 42" 46" 47" 48" 50" 55" 60" 65" 70" 75" BY PRICE FIND YOUR TVBY PRICE Under $500 $501 - $1,000 $1,001 - $1,500 $1,501 - $2,000 BY BRAND FIND YOUR TVBY BRAND Current Discontinued BY TESTRESULTS FIND YOUR TVBY TEST RESULTS Current Discontinued Reflections Motion Blur Viewing Angle Input Lag Contrast Ratio Black Uniformity Gray Uniformity Reflections Motion Blur Viewing Angle Input Lag Contrast Ratio Black Uniformity Updated Apr 10, 2015 By Cedric Demers Samsung 2015 LED TVs Reviews and Prices Search Current TVs Lineup Smart Features Samsung J4000 OVERVIEW SPECIFICATIONS PRICE HISTORY Samsung J5500 OVERVIEW SPECIFICATIONS PRICE HISTORY Samsung J6300 OVERVIEW SPECIFICATIONS PRICE HISTORY 8.2 Samsung JU6500 REVIEW COMPARE SETTINGS SPECIFICATIONS PRICE HISTORY 8.2 Samsung JU6700 REVIEW COMPARE SETTINGS SPECIFICATIONS PRICE HISTORY 8.4 Samsung JU7100 REVIEW COMPARE SETTINGS SPECIFICATIONS PRICE HISTORY Samsung JU7500 OVERVIEW SPECIFICATIONS PRICE HISTORY Samsung JS8500 OVERVIEW SPECIFICATIONS PRICE HISTORY Samsung JS9000 OVERVIEW SPECIFICATIONS PRICE HISTORY Samsung JS9500 OVERVIEW SPECIFICATIONS PRICE HISTORY Our Tools By Needs Chart 2014 2013 Deals Learn about TVs Plasma vs LED Summary Picture Quality Electricity Cost Cost and Longevity Thickness and Weight How They Work Market Refresh Rate Refresh Rate Fake Refresh Rates Soap Opera Effect 24p Playback Resolutions Resolution 4k vs 1080p 4k Content Size to Distance Best Gaming TVs Smart TVs 3D Local Dimming Plasma Filter Aspect Ratio Image Retention Warranty SAMSUNG LED TVS SAMSUNG SMART TV PLATFORM We’ve begun reviewing Samsung’s 2015 TVs, including its 4k lineup. So far, all have good picture quality, but pricier models have more features, prettier designs, and better screen finishes. Samsung’s smart features aren’t as good as they were in the past. In 2015, the company switched to its Tizen operating system for their TVs. As a result, there are fewer apps available than on older Samsung smart TVs. Netflix and YouTube are available, but Amazon Instant and Hulu Plus are not (though they should be added soon). The interface and point-and-click smart remote (available with higher-end TVs) are still great. Picture quality-wise, Samsung LED TVs are quite good. They have good contrast, don’t reflect much light, and handle motion quite well. They also have low input lag when they are in Game mode, making them a solid choice for a gaming TV.   2015 Lineup Description and Reviews Samsung J4000 32" CHECK PRICE The Samsung J4000 is a barebones, entry-level TV. It’s only available in 32”, and its design is not the prettiest. It also has few inputs, but we expect its picture quality will be good enough to make it a fine choice for a small 720p set. This is a 60Hz TV, so it does not have the motion interpolation feature. It also has no smart features, so this won’t be a good choice if you want built-in streaming capabilities. See our review Samsung J5500 40" to 50" CHECK PRICE The Samsung J5500 is a basic smart TV. It doesn’t come with a smart remote, so people who want to make frequent use of their TV’s smart features should probably opt for a higher-end model. We expect it will have decent picture quality, and its design is almost shockingly pretty, given that it’s not a top-tier TV. See our review Samsung J6300 32" to 75" CHECK PRICE Samsung’s top 1080p TV, the J6300 is similar to the J5500, but comes with the ability to interpolate frames up to 120 fps. Like the J5500, this TV does not come with a smart remote, meaning it isn’t quite as good as the 4k models when it comes to smart features. We expect its picture quality will be good. As far as design goes, it’s not quite as good-looking as the J5500.  See our review 8.2 Samsung JU6500 40" to 75" CHECK PRICE Samsung’s entry-level 4k smart TV, the JU6500 has mostly-good picture quality, and low input lag. It has a couple of notable flaws, though, like having a bit too much motion blur, as well as judder when displaying 24 fps content. It can also only interpolate frames up to 60 fps, which means fans of the soap opera effect might prefer the JU7100. Still, its good contrast and its smart remote make it a good option for those looking for a TV for general use. See our review 8.2 Samsung JU6700 40" to 65" CHECK PRICE Pound for pound, the Samsung JU6700 is the same as the cheaper JU6500. The only difference is that it has a curved screen, and comes with a fancy smart remote. If you really like the aesthetics of a curved TV, this is one of your more affordable options. If you don’t care and just want a good TV, either save money by getting the JU6500 or put the extra towards an upgrade to the JU7100.  See our review 8.4 Samsung JU7100 40" to 75" CHECK PRICE The JU7100 is a pretty great TV. Like the JU6500, it has good contrast and uniformity, as well as low input lag. The JU7100 has less motion blur, though, which makes it a solid choice for general viewing, watching sports, and gaming alike. The main issue here is that the HDMI inputs are not on the TV itself, but rather in the included One Connect Mini box. That means an increase in clutter around your set. Still, in terms of overall picture quality for the price, this is a really good TV, and is likely to remain our #1 4k TV for 2015.  See our review Samsung JU7500 40" to 78" CHECK PRICE This TV is just like the JU7100, but with a curved screen. Unless you want one for its looks, we don’t recommend buying curved TVs. Any benefit to the curved screen is minimal, and the price difference is pretty big. Save some money by getting the JU7100. See our review Samsung JS8500 48" to 65" CHECK PRICE The Samsung JS8500 is the cheapest Samsung 4k TV with Quantum Dot technology. It’s a feature that is meant to increase color space and create better overall picture. The TV is also HDR-capable, which is a feature that increases the dynamic range to deliver brighter whites. See our review Samsung JS9000 48" to 65" CHECK PRICE The Samsung JS9000 has similar specs to the JS8500, but it has a curved screen and comes with a full-sized One Connect box instead of the mini version. The picture quality is likely similar to the JS8500. See our review Samsung JS9500 65" to 88" CHECK PRICE The JS9500 is Samsung’s flagship TV for 2015. Like the JS8500 and JS9000, it has Quantum Dot technology and HDR capability. It also comes with a full-size One Connect Box. It also has several features no other Samsung TV has. Notably, this includes a full-array backlight, which should help the local dimming function. It also comes with a built-in camera. We expect it has good contrast and overall picture quality. It’s also worth noting that its design is stunning. See our review Conclusion Whatever your needs or price range, Samsung’s 2015 lineup has you covered. Their price-to-quality ratio isn’t the best, but it’s easy to buy a Samsung TV with confidence that it will be a good purchase.  FIND YOUR TVBY SIZE 32" 40" 42" 46" 47" 48" 50" 55" 60" 65" 70" 75" Questions & Answers 48 ANSWERED QUESTIONS 28 Do you think there will be a big difference compared to last year''s LED TVs? Usually, the difference in picture quality is minimal. The picture quality of Samsung LED TVs have hit a plateau in the last few years (except in terms of backlight uniformity). This is why Samsung has put more emphasis on their extra software features and design.\r Update: Indeed the picture quality is about the same, except for the improved uniformity. Apr 10, 2014 18 Do you do any testing of the Vizio brand? We will start testing it next month.\r Update: We reviewed all three series: the E Series, the M Series and the P Series. They are great budget TVs. Jul 16, 2014 17 I just noticed on your site that Samsung''s UHD TVs all have a panel refresh rate of 120Hz, whereas their top HD models have 240Hz refresh rate. (I think you had the UHD models listed as 240Hz too up until as week ago) Do you know the reason for this? Why would their flagship TVs have a lower refresh rate? There is currently no 4k TV with 240Hz on the market. It doesn''t really matter, though, because the refresh rate isn''t an indicator of motion blur (check out our motion blur test pictures). Jun 05, 2014 16 Is there a visible difference in picture quality between the Samsung HU8550 and the HU9000? We haven''t tested the HU9000 yet, but we do not expect a big difference. It''s mostly the curvature of the HU9000 and the better sound. Apr 28, 2014 14 What is the difference between the UN65H6300 and UN65H6350? Which would you rate higher? We haven''t tested the UN65H6300. We expect the picture quality to be the same; it is just Costco''s version of it. Aug 24, 2014 13 What is the difference between the Samsung h6350 and H6203? We don''t expect a difference in picture quality. We will test the H6203 in a few weeks to confirm this.\r Update: Indeed, the picture quality is the same. However, the design is uglier and the smart features are slower. Sep 22, 2014 10 Is it worth paying $200 more for a quad processor in this year''s TVs vs the same model from last year, which comes with a dual processor? Not unless you plan on using the smart TV features a lot. Apr 10, 2014 10 I need a new TV and am not just upgrading for the fun. I heard it stated that you should not buy a new outdated TV set (1080P). The 4k sets are still expensive, but their prices are dropping and they are the new TV of the future. I am interested in a 65 inch by Samsung and NO CURVE. What set should I buy since I "need" a new TV? It depends how far you are sitting away from it. If it is more than 10 feet, just get a 1080p like the UN65H7150. You won''t see the difference with 4k, assuming a good 1080p bit rate. If you are closer, get the UN65HU8550. Aug 01, 2014 10 Are you guys planning on reviewing the Panasonic TC-55AS680U, or any of the 2014 Panasonic LED TVs? I''ve been trying to compare it to the Samsung H7150, which I''m leaning towards getting to replace a broken Panasonic TC-P55ST60. Not anytime soon. Panasonic LED TVs are less popular than their plasma TVs. Most of them use LG IPS panels inside. We might get to it in the fall after we''ve finished with Vizio and Sharp, if we have time. Aug 23, 2014 9 Which will be a better buy, the Samsung UN48H5500 or Sony KDL48W600B LED TV? We haven''t tested the H5500 yet, but we expect the picture quality to be in the same ballpark. Samsung has better smart features and apps, though, so if you plan on using them a lot, go for the Samsung. Jun 23, 2014 8 How is the testing of the Vizio E, M, series going? I am looking forward to your expert review of these competitive HDTVs. It has been delayed, but we should be back on track to start reviewing TVs by the end of the week. We took a break to clean up our website and we underestimated the time it would take to do that. The E series (60") will be the first one to be reviewed, followed by the M series (55") shortly after.\r \r Update: The reviews are up now. Sep 08, 2014 7 I''m comparing the F8000 and H8000. I understand the H8000 loses the camera but gains a "smarter" hub. Is there any difference in picture quality between the two models? Also you mentioned above that the H8000 is edge lit, so the local dimming isn''t very useful. I''m assuming this would be true of the F8000 as well. How about the F7100 or H7150 that you were comparing in the question? No difference in picture quality, and both are edge-lit, so the local dimming works the same way. We haven''t tested last year''s F7100, but we don''t also expect a difference in terms of picture quality compared to this year''s H7150. Jun 10, 2014 7 Between the F5500 and the h5550, which is the best?\r I will use it for gaming and watching movies. They are the same. The H5500 is just the 2014 refresh with updated software. Get the cheaper one. Sep 22, 2014 5 Which one should I buy now, the F9000 or HU8550? They are very similar. Just get whichever one is cheaper. Jun 15, 2014 3 How would last year''s F7100 compare to the H7150 with the improved microdimming pro feature? I''m more or less concerned about whether the black levels would be improved, as well as the claims of better color and sharpness. No, it''s the same. Micro dimming is software only, so panel''s actual contrast stays the same. The H8000 does have local dimming, but because it is edge lit, it isn''t very precise, so it''s pretty much useless. May 25, 2014 3 If I buy the Samsung H6350, would I be able to get the Soap Opera Effect when I play single player video games? If possible I would like to know how to set it up to Max Level. Yes. Set ''Auto Motion Plus'' to ''Smooth''. However, this isn''t recommended for gaming because it adds too much input lag. Some people don''t mind the lag, though. Aug 24, 2014 3 I''m looking for a 50" LED and the following models are available in my area at Walmart: Vizio E500I-B1, LG 50LB5900, and Samsung UN50H5203AFXZA. Which one would you recommend? They all seem to have horrible reviews and customer service. Should I pay much attention to them? I do not need all the bells and whistles, i.e. Smart. Just a basic, good TV in my bedroom where I do watch TV at night. If you don''t care about extra features, get the Vizio. It is a good basic TV. Oct 07, 2014 2 Does the audio out mini jack on the H5500 40" mean 3.5mm jack? Yes. Jun 15, 2014 2 I have just bought a Panasonic E6 and I noticed a little blur, just a little. Can you please make a review of it? This is a discontinued model so we won''t review it. Only a little blur is normal for an LED TV. As you can see in our motion blur pictures, all of them have some. Aug 23, 2014 2 The Panasonic TH-42AS630D IPS panel looked brighter and clearer when compared with the LG 42LB5820 IPS panel. What is the difference between IPS panels of LG and the IPS LED LCD Super Bright panel of Panasonic? Not sure if it is worth going for Panasonic. Panasonic doesn''t produce IPS panels, they actually buy them from LG. The difference that you saw is either caused by different picture settings, or the backlight is stronger on the Panasonic. Sep 29, 2014 2 Will you review any Sharp televisions? It is unlikely that we will have time this year, so it will have to wait for 2015. Oct 17, 2014 2 Trying to decide between the UN65H7150 or the UN75H6350. The price difference is about $600 for 10 extra inches. I will be sitting about 12-13 feet back. 10 extra inches is a big size difference, it is definitely noticeable and a good upgrade. At your distance, a 75" won''t be too big (after the initial shock, of course). That said, it all depends on how you value your money. If you feel that you will regret your decision because $600 is a lot for you, get the smaller 65". It is still a good size for your distance. As for the picture quality difference, it is less significant than the size. The biggest difference is that the H7150 has a better uniformity and screen finish, but you will appreciate the bigger screen of the H6350 more. Nov 18, 2014 2 Trying to decide between the Samsung UHD 4K 55HU7250 Curved TV and the Samsung 60H7150 flat TV. I would like to know if the curved TV makes is much of an improvement over the flat TV for those that would be viewing the TV off-center. I have a en eight ft couch directly facing the TV and then on the left side and right side of the room two love seats that I would like guests to be able to sit on and still see a decent picture when watching a game. The couch is about nine ft from the screen and the two loveseats are about three feet in front of the screen and about four feet from the edge of the screen. Also, does one of the screens have better picture quality than the other when looking straight on at the screen? Thanks! A curved TV is more of a gimmick than anything else. It slightly improves the experience when you are directly in front, but it diminishes it if you are off-axis. We didn''t test the UN55HU7250, but the picture quality should be similar to the UN60H7150, except for the 4k resolution. If the UN55HU7250 is pricier, you will be happier with the UN60H7150 instead. Nov 26, 2014 2 What is the best value to quality 55" ultra HD television? The Samsung UN55HU8550 has the best picture quality. If you want something cheaper, you can get the UN55HU6840. Jan 02, 2015 2 Now that CES is over, when can I expect 2014 models to drop in price? They won''t go down much. However, when new models hit the stores (around April), retailers will want to get rid of their old stock, so you might get a really good deal if you go in person and haggle a little bit. Popular models will be out of stock fast, though, so there is a risk in waiting. Jan 12, 2015 1 I have just purchased a Samsung un55fh6030. I am having trouble making the proper adjustments. How do I maximize picture quality and get rid of the soap opera effect? I have all motion settings off. Also, what is the minimum distance to sit from the set for proper viewing? Any setting recommendations? We posted our calibration settings in the Q&A section of our review of the UN55FH6030. Turning off the setting called Auto Motion Plus will get rid of the soap opera effect. A distance of eight feet would be ideal. May 27, 2014 1 On Samsung''s website, the HU8550 is said to support UHD upscaling. Does that mean that if I play HD content from YouTube from smart hub, or HD content from Comcast or HD content from Apple TV, HU8550 is able to upscale the HD content to UHD content and display it as UHD? Yes, but don''t expect a significant difference as compared to a 1080p TV. Upscaling can''t create new information, but rather makes a guess. More info here. Jun 08, 2014 1 I am looking for a 40 or 42 inch smart TV. I''m not well informed on LED vs plasma, cameras, and all that stuff. I know very little about the technology. I do not play video games, and am not into sports much either. I enjoy relaxing after work with a good TV program. What''s the best TV for my needs at the most affordable price? The Sony KDL40W600B should be good for you, as long as you don''t frequently use the smart features (which are somewhat slow). It is affordable and the picture quality is quite good. Aug 22, 2014 1 How do I check the quality of my Samsung TV? Watch something on it!\r But seriously, give it a watch. Are you happy with it while watching the stuff that you normally watch? If so, don''t worry beyond that. All LED TVs have flaws. If you start actively looking for them, you will just be disappointed in your new TV. Aug 25, 2014 1 Samsung is surely the most notable maker of tv sets, but can you add Philips TVs to your review selection? They have a lot of selection and seem to be a pretty good value for money. Maybe in the fall, if we can get to it. We plan on reviewing some Vizio and Sharp TVs before then. Sep 02, 2014 1 I''m looking to buy a TV before this year is up. Which TVs will you be reviewing for November and December? The next one is the Samsung UN40H5500. After that, we will take a break from reviewing TVs for a while to clean up our website, update articles, and prepare for next year. We might do one or two more before the end of the year if a specific model gets requested often, but not more than that. We are currently hiring, so next year we will be able to review more TVs. Nov 01, 2014 1 Please suggest me which smart TV should I choose between the Samsung H5500 seriess or H6203 series. They both cost the same price, but the H6203 has a 120 Hz refresh rate and 240 CMR, but single core processor, whereas the H5500 has faster quad core, but 60 refresh and 120 CMR. I will be using some apps on my smart TV, but not a whole lot, though. Mostly Netflix, YouTube, more news apps, FB, Dailymotion, etc. which one should i go for? The H6203 has better picture quality, especially in terms of motion. As you mentioned though, the apps are a lot slower. So it depends what you value more: picture quality or faster apps. You will probably prefer picture quality, so go for the H6203. Nov 25, 2014 1 I plan to buy a 75"+ TV for my game room/home theater. I''m comparing the Samsung HU8550 and H7150. Considering we will keep it forever (and that $ doesn''t matter that much, but I don''t want a bad deal), I am leaning toward 4k so that it lasts in terms of technology. Which of these would you choose? Is there another brand that you would choose (for size... size matters). For that size and if price doesn''t matter much, get the HU8550. You will appreciate the 4k at that size, and it will last you longer. It is a great TV. Nov 29, 2014 1 I want to upgrade from a UN55D8000 for a 75" or higher TV for a viewing distance of about 11.5 ft. I don''t watch much 3D, but am not opposed to watching 3D content on a larger TV. I''m thinking UN75H7150 would do, but the price is a bit steep for my pockets. I''d do it, but only if there isn''t another you could recommend? I notice you don''t seem to review Sharp products? I was curious about their Quattron technology. Thanks. If the price is outside your budget, get the cheaper UN75H6350. The picture quality isn''t far off. We didn''t have time to review Sharp TVs this year, unfortunately. Dec 23, 2014 1 Best non-smart TV, 50-60"? I''m in the market for a new TV. There''s not much point in looking for a "dumb" TV. Only very cheap (and generally poor quality) TVs have no smart functions at all. If you''re looking for a solid budget TV in that size range, both the Samsung H6350 and the Vizio E-series have good overall picture quality, and would make good picks. Mar 12, 2015 0 What is the difference between a regular Samsung flat screen bought in 2012 and a smart TV? A smart TV is really just a normal TV with software apps like Netflix built in. You can easily turn a ''dumb'' TV into a smart one by purchasing a third party device like an Apple TV, Roku, or Chromecast. The smart part of the TV is independent of the picture quality. Aug 04, 2014 0 Will you review any Panasonic LED TVs for 2014? I doubt we will have time this year, unfortunately. Oct 31, 2014 0 I second the request to review Panasonic TVs. They have been a major player in the Plasma arena and I would like to see how their LEDs stand up against the other major brands before Black Friday. Indeed, the plasma TVs that we reviewed last year were really great. Unfortunately, we won''t have time this year to review their LEDs. Nov 02, 2014 0 I am looking to buy a nice TV and am confused between the Samsung H6350 50" and Samsung HU6950 50". Which one do you think is a good choice overall? We didn''t test the HU6950. It looks like the same TV, but with a different resolution. For a 50", 4k is not really worth it at a normal viewing distance, so just get the cheaper of the two. Nov 17, 2014 0 I just bought the Samsung h7150 55" TV and am wondering if it is normal to see a thin shadow-like edge on left side of the screen (about five pixels wide)? Is this normal for this model TV, or might it be an issue? It depends what you mean by this. It will be helpful if you could provide a picture of the issue. It is probably a defect, though, so exchange your TV while it is still under the store''s return policy. Nov 24, 2014 0 Which sets provide the best picture, true to the Cinema form, when watching movies? Of course, this would be through disabling motion controls that create the Soap Opera Effect. Some sets, when you disable all of the motion controls, introduce extensive judder and then you get caught up in a Catch 22 situation. I am currently looking at the Samsung HU8550. Judder shouldn''t be an issue. Just make sure your Blu-ray player outputs at 24p and also that you didn''t disable that option on your TV. The HU8550 is a great TV, so go for it if it fits your budget. Nov 25, 2014 0 I am looking for a 75" TV or bigger for a family room. The room is mid-level light-wise for most of the day, except late afternoon when there is direct sunlight coming from the side. Will be primarily used for Netflix and sports viewing. Picture quality to value is primary concern (I will be switching out from a Pioneer Kuro 60" which I have enjoyed). The 4 choices I have narrowed down to with approx price are as follows: Samsung HU8550 ($5,000), Samsung H7150 ($3,000), Vizio M series 80" ($2,500) and Samsung H6350 ($2,000). I''d appreciate your advice on which offers the best bang for the buck, considering this will likely be my main TV for the next five years. Thanks. For the best bang for your buck, just get the Samsung UN75H6350. The price difference with the other TVs can''t really be justified in that size range. The Vizio feels cheaper, the H7150 is better, but not $1,000 better (unless you plan on using the extra features, or really want the better screen finish), and the HU8550 is really overpriced in that size just for 4k. Dec 01, 2014 0 I was reviewing your site and you had me set on the Samsung H7150. I went to purchase it today and noticed the price went up $400 from last night, so I started scrolling around to find a cheaper price and then came across the Samsung 55" 4K Ultra HD Smart TV - UN55HU6840 on a cyber Monday (weekly deal) for $997. What is the difference between the two models? Would I be better off with the 4k? I also noticed it was 60hz, not sure if that''s a big factor. We didn''t test the HU6840. It is a budget 4k TV with fewer features than the H7150. Therefore, we expect the H7150 to have better overall picture quality for content with a resolution of 1080p or under. Dec 03, 2014 0 Does Samsung use cheaper components in the TVs made for the big discount stores such as BJ''s? Not to our knowledge, no. TVs with the same model number should be of the same quality, regardless of where you purchase them. Mar 17, 2015 0 First off, great site. I had a plasma 720p TV, a Panasonic, and was hesitant to upgrade based on reading here that plasmas are better in many respects. I bought this after receiving email from your site showing there was a price drop at Best Buy and was NOT disappointed. I definitely see some differences, but the overall picture is so much better. I use the web browser to go to CBS and catch up on shows, since CBS does not do Hulu. \r My question is, after starting to watch an episode from the CBS website, I have had the TV freeze, restart, and even show a message stating there was not enough memory to watch the show. Is there anything I can do differently to keep watching on the TV without these issues? Unfortunately, this is likely a limitation of the TV. Some Smart TVs are buggier than others, and have weaker computing capabilities, and so they won''t be able to sustain intensive activity like streaming video in-browser. \r If you want to watch CBS streaming on your TV, your best bet would probably be to connect a separate device. A laptop with an HDMI connection would work, or a screen-mirroring device like a Chromecast could do the trick by displaying content from your computer''s browser. These should be more stable options, and would not run out of memory while playing the stream. Mar 20, 2015 0 I''m having a hard time finding a compatible pair of over the ear, wireless headphones for my Samsung UN60H7100AFXZA I bought at Costco. I can''t tell you how many people I''ve called (Samsung Tech support, Best Buy, Sony etc), and no one seems to know about one Bluetooth device talking to the other. Can you help? I find your answers to others knowledgeable and helpful. Thanks in advance. You should be able to connect a pair of Bluetooth headphones, but unfortunately, we don''t have any specific recommendations, as we currently don''t review headphones. Any Bluetooth headphones should be compatible, though. Mar 23, 2015 0 Can you review the new Samsung UN60JU6500? It is 4K but at a $1,750 no-3D price point which seems to fill a good gap. We currently have a UN55JU6500 here. The review should be posted on the website this week. Apr 07, 2015 0 Which is the better TV, the Samsung HU8550 or the JU6700? The two are about even for uniformity, but the HU8550 has slightly better contrast and less motion blur, as well as support for 24p playback. The JU6700 can also only interpolate frames up to 60 hz, whereas the HU8550 can interpolate up to 120 hz. Overall, the HU8550 is the better TV. Apr 15, 2015 Have a question? Before asking a question, make sure you read our recommendations by size or our recommendations by price range, as well as use the search function of our website. Alternatively, you can send us an email at advice@rtings.com. Due to the high volume of questions received, we no longer accept questions outside the United States. Thank you for your understanding. Mobile Site Desktop Site Mobile Site Desktop Site About us Privacy Policy Contact us Jobs Sitemap © 2015 Rtings.com'),
