re this, and that did''t stand the test of time, was so \r slow/unresponsive by the end of the contract I ended up slamming it against \r a table.\r \r Speed - Still lightening quick, haven''t rebooted the system since i''ve had it \r (2.3 Gingerbread), it took months for it to have a little fit where i''d asked \r it to do something too quickly and took a couple of seconds to catch up. I began \r to wonder if it ever would have a slow down, but does it every now and then \r more recently i''d say once a week for about a second.\r \r Sensitivity - Still very responsive, and calibrated perfectly (the hero used \r to think i''d pressed an inch over on the other side of the phone sometimes)\r \r Battery - I''m unsure on whether i''ve got too many apps running or haven''t set \r up battery options properly, but my battery lasts just about a day of moderate \r use (music walking to and from work - 1hr, 1hr - phone call at least followed \r by an 1hr here or there browsing the web.)\r \r Durability - I never bought a case for the phone, I don''t like them, so it''s \r been braving the elements from day 1. I''m quite clumsy sometimes (as you can \r probably tell from the way i''ve typed this review up) the phone has been drop \r quite a few times even on it''s face from waste height, and hasn''t even got a \r crack or suffered from it. I have had it out in the pouring raining trying to \r change songs (it was impossible to) but it never suffered water damage either, \r so it''s top notch in that area too.\r \r Verdict: I''m so happy with this phone still, I don''t think i''m gonna be happy \r to upgrade as easily as I have done in the past, most of my old phones were \r knackered by upgrade time and I was counting down the days, however with this \r i''m considering just keeping it and selling the upgrade, or keeping it as a \r festival phone perhaps. You can''t go wrong with this phone. My mates girlfriend \r just got a contract on this for 600mins, 1GB internet and unlimited texts at \r ?19 per month, and this in my opinion is a phenomenal deal!\r \r Hope that helps!\r Rating: \r \r \r Reviewed by Matt C from England on 15th Nov 2012\r Well, I thought it is about time I put in my review of this phone since I bought \r it based on reviews on this site.\r \r I should highlight now that I am not a power user, and there are a lot of features \r on this phone I have simply never needed to use. I came from an iPhone 3G so \r getting to grips with Android took a little while, but overall I think it is \r a good OS. However, it does seem to lack the simplicity of iOS and whilst iOS \r feels very linear, it just works. As an overall experience, I have to say iOS \r is a lot more user friendly, and a lot easier to get on with. I appreciate the \r lure of Android for power users, but for people like me a lot of the ability \r of Android is lost.\r \r I have used the phone for just over a year now, and in that time it has been \r near faultless.\r \r I have always used a faux leather flip front case, so my screen is still like \r new, which is nice. I have dropped it quite a few times and although the case \r has seen better days, the phone itself is still going strong. However I have \r had 13 months out of a ?3.50 case which is an achievement!\r \r The screen is superb on this phone. Granted, by todays standard it is last gen \r quality but I have never had an issue with it. Throughout a year of use it has \r remained responsive and I have not suffered the ''pink tinge'' problem that some \r users were reporting back when I bought it.\r \r All of the buttons still work, although I think the ''home'' button has developed \r a fault recently. I have never had the OS lock up, or any of the other random \r problems that some have reported. I should note that my phone is on an O2 contract, \r and whilst I have never had any issues with the OS, I find that system updates \r for this phone have been pretty non-existent through my network. Having never \r bothered with Kies, I expect that is partly my own fault but my partner uses \r a Desire HD and she has had around 3 updates in 18 months (On Vodafone) without \r the need for proprietary software. I have had none at all on the S2 in 13 months \r of use :( However, that is not a failing of the phone as far as I am aware, \r but of the network.\r \r I have also never suffered from poor signal as others have. Both telephone signal \r and wi-fi have been consistently good and I am more than happy with the reliability. \r On that note, call quality has also been consistently good, and even though \r the phone has been dropped a few times on hard surfaces, both the earpiece speaker \r and mic still function fine. The loud speaker is ok, but a little quieter than \r other phones I have used. However it is still perfectly functional and does \r the job, albeit not quite as well as other phones.\r \r A big issue for this phone has always been battery life, and because of this \r I prepared by purchasing an upgraded battery! However, it is still in my cupboard \r at home, unopened. For my personal use, I have found the battery is lacking \r in some circumstances, but my lifestyle means I have rarely been caught short. \r I accept that for other users, battery life has been worse, but for my use it \r has been acceptable. I tend to charge my S2 once every 1.5 - 2 days. However \r if I have had a mad browsing session or have been playing heavily on a certain \r game involving a catapult and irate poultry, it soon depletes! But seeing as \r my wi-fi is always on at home, and I have emails synching regularly too, the \r battery lasts long enough for me. I have found tweaking screen settings has \r helped, as well as restricting social networking sites and turning off haptic \r feedback. \r \r Internet connectivity and browsing has always been flawless, and fast. However, \r I find there are a few issues at the moment with the web browser occasionally \r locking up. I think, though, this may be down to some unwanted bloatware rather \r than any fault of the phone. The browsing experience is quite fluid once you \r get used to it, and you can add and manage favourites with relative ease. One \r thing that is frustrating, though, is that you can''t close down the browser \r completely without using task manager. When only one browser window is left \r open, it would be nice to be able to close it and exit to home screen. But you \r can''t, so your browser is always open in the background unless you close it \r via task manager. Another element of the browser that I think could have been \r tweaked is the downloads page. Once you have viewed a download and deleted it \r from your list, it does not delete the file from the media folder. It would \r have been nice to have the option to delete both for those occasions where you \r download something only to decide you don''t actually want it. It just means \r having to delete things manually, but it would have been nice if they could \r have incorporated a menu where you get the choice to delete the actual media \r at the same time. All in all, though, these are very minor gripes. One final \r point to mention is that I use wi-fi when at home and during longer browsing \r sessions the phone gets quite warm. It concerned me to start with because I \r wondered if it was going to cause any damage, or premature screen burn out but \r thus far I have seen no ill effects but I accept that at only 13 months old \r there is time for it to develop some yet.\r \r One major gripe that I currently have, though, revolves around non-removable \r programs, one in particular. I am, of course, talking about voice talk! I think \r my ''home'' button may be faulty now because even after only one press, voice \r talk opens and is doing so with annoying regularity at the moment. Suffice to \r say I wanted to remove it, but can''t. I could live with that if I could just \r turn it off, but alas I can''t. For a supposed fully customisable operating system, \r I find that curious and a bit annoying.\r \r One thing I have used quite a lot is the camera, and I have to say for a phone \r camera (and a Samsung one at that) it is pretty respectable. It has plenty of \r settings and takes some good quality snaps. Browsing the media folder is easy \r as is sharing media via social networks or MMS/email. OK, it is no DSLR, but \r it is better than my partners 10mp Samsung compact digital camera. Video recording \r is great if the light is good, but in low light conditions it gives very noisy \r footage. I can''t really complain though as it is a phone, not a camcorder! Although \r the phone comes with editing software, I have never used it so I cannot comment \r on that.\r \r Texting is quite easy, but then I only use the standard Samsung keyboard. I \r tried the ''swype'' and keypad sweeping settings and found it to be unreliable \r and clunky - more of a marketing gimmick than a real-world feature. I daresay \r I could have kept at it, but if it isn''t broke, don''t fix it, right? A point \r I want to make here is how fragmented some of the OS options are. For instance, \r in messaging you can set many options for SMS, MMS etc, but there are no settings \r for input which would lead you to believe there are none. So you have to exit \r and go to the main system settings in order to change that. Except you don''t, \r you just have to press and hold the screen in your message field and an input \r menu opens. There is yet another menu in the keyboard itself for changing predictive \r text and other options. Being new to Android, I have always felt it is counter \r intuitive to have so many fragmented options menus, but as I have become more \r experienced I have become more familiar with how Android and Touchwiz work so \r I have reached a state of competence. That said, why can''t all the settings \r for messaging be in one place? Finally, this phone will not let you send SMS \r messages greater than 3 messages long. I have no idea why. Anything longer than \r 3 messages gets automatically converted into an MMS, and there is no way of \r changing it that I could find. As with everything else though, these things \r are minor gripes, but if they were addressed they would go a long way to making \r the experience a little more enjoyable.\r \r One feature that I found out about by complete accident is this phone can be \r used as a turn by turn satnav! Granted, it kills the battery, but when your \r actual satnav dies unexpectedly when you are in the middle of London, it is \r a really nice surprise to find out your phone can do the job just as well! I \r was actually speechless that it worked so effectively, and got me to my next \r appointment on time. I have used it several times since and although it works \r brilliantly in major cities, it is a little more hit and miss in countryside \r areas. That said, as a backup I think it is an awesome feature.\r \r I have never used this phone for music, so I cannot comment on that element.\r \r Emailing is a fairly nice experience, and the phone has the built in ability \r to view .pdf, .doc and .xls files and the ability to edit the latter two as \r well. I use a Blackberry as a work phone, and the S2 surpasses it for it''s ability \r to open complex documents. I also like how the S2 synchs with my mailbox so \r if I delete something on my phone, it removes it from the servers inbox too. \r However, I use my S2 with a Hotmail account and have never been able to get \r it to work with the junk folder. There is a list of all the folders that I have \r in my account, but if I select junk, it says ''refreshing'' but nothing ever loads. \r This is a little frustrating as sometimes I get important emails come through \r that go to junk and I would like to be able to access that folder in the same \r way I do my inbox without having to use the internet browser to log into my \r account. Overall, though, emailing is a good enough experience and the phone \r handles things competently.\r \r Apps are easy to come by, and the Play store is easy enough to navigate. However, \r I feel that a lot of apps want unreasonable access privileges to my phone, and \r because of that I am very selective with what I install. The previously mentioned \r title involving irate poultry is one example. Initially the app only wanted \r basic access rights, but as soon as the next update came out it was asking for \r a lot more. Why does a game I play need to know my GPS location? Why does it \r need to know who I am talking to on my phone? I don''t believe it should need \r any more access than phone state so that it can allow incoming calls etc. I \r didn''t update because of these unreasonable ''rights''. What frustrates me about \r the Play store is that some of the main titles are not available to buy. They \r are free ''ad supported'' apps that are nothing more than a front to mine personal \r data from people in my opinion. I am very careful with what I install on my \r S2, and other than a couple of apps, it has remained pretty much as it was when \r I had it.\r \r Every day elements of this phone are also present and functional. Calendar, \r alarm clock, calculator etc. There appears to be a bug with my phone where if \r I press my clock display it will not open the clock menu. I had to put a separate \r shortcut on my home page for the clock to access it. It''s only a little niggle, \r but one I believe should not be there.\r \r Overall, I have been really happy with this phone. It has taken some getting \r used to but it is a brilliant phone for the money when compared to it''s closest \r rivals. At the time I bought it, it was over ?200 cheaper than the iPhone 4S \r and did everything the 4S did and more. This was bang for buck the best phone \r on the market and whilst it is dated now it still packs a mighty punch for it''s \r current price and is still ?200 cheaper than the 4S. I would recommend the S2 \r to those who want a versatile phone but do not want to pay the earth. Granted \r it is not a top spec phone by todays standards, but for the money it is a great \r choice.\r \r I have decided to give the Nexus 4 a try and see if I can finally settle into \r Android. I will be keeping my S2 as a backup though as although it feels less \r intuitive to me than my 3G, it has not only been reliable but also extremely \r useful.\r Rating: \r Reply by S21 from UK on 15th Nov 2012\r You''ve said it all, Matt! Thanks for taking the time to write such a detailed \r review.\r \r \r Reviewed by roger.stark from israel on 13th Nov 2012\r the.best.phone.of.them.alleven.better.than.samsung.3\r Rating: \r \r \r Reviewed by shelly from uk on 22nd Oct 2012\r Amazing phone, i love it! i have got in the pink and it looks soo nice, super \r fast.Was using the blackberry 9790 before and that seems so slow now.\r Rating: \r \r \r Reviewed by Sumant from UK on 21st Sep 2012\r Amzing fatures and definitely the best phone on market before S3 although a \r real awful battery life. I am into 15th month of my contract of 18 months and \r I have to recharge battery after 6-7 hrs of use . Intemittently disconnecting \r HD screen interface. \r Overall big bang mobile but as usual a very very poor batter... characteristic \r of samsung. Disappointment. \r Rating: \r \r \r Reviewed by ace from Jamaica on 6th Sep 2012\r Such a device.I am walking around with my laptop.and phone all in one a give \r the SII a 5 ratings\r Rating: \r \r \r Reviewed by rahman.M from uk on 4th Sep 2012\r All rounder Galaxy s2 Android is a very good quality light weight truly smart \r phone.Get it enjoy it.I used it for seven months no complain. \r Rating: \r \r \r Reviewed by Sam from Kenya on 31st Aug 2012\r I bought the S2 phone two months ago, Good phone but i cant upgrade to ICS with \r kies, The phone also keeps hanging time and again. who has an idea?\r Rating: \r \r \r Reviewed by MEL